solutions.content:
**Strategy:** 
The idea is to count fresh oranges and store indices of all rotten oranges given in the starting. Then traverse through these stored indices and if any fresh orange is found in all the four directions of these indices, we will make it rotten orange and reduce the fresh oranges count by one. At last, if fresh oranges count is 0, we will return total time elapsed till now. Else return -1. 

*So, how we should store and traverse through the rotten orange indices and count time elapsed?* 
Answer is to use **BFS(Breadth First Search)** technique. The key observation to use this technique is that assume all the initial rotten oranges are at level 0. Then the adjacent fresh oranges to these rotten oranges are in level 1 and are rotten on day 1 and the next in level 2 and rotten on day 2 and so on.  This is similar to level order traversal and therefore, the time required to rot all the possible fresh oranges will be equal to the number of levels.
As we will be using BFS, so we will store indices of rotten oranges in queue.

**Approach:**
1. Initialize a queue for breadth first search in which we will store indices of rotten oranges and freshOranges variable to count number of fresh oranges present in the grid initially. Also initialize our answer variable time.
	```
	int freshOranges = 0, time = 0;
	queue<pair<int, int>> q; 
	```
2. Iterate over the entire grid and add indices of all the rotten oranges in the queue and also keep counting the number of fresh oranges.
	```
	for(int i = 0; i < grid.size(); i++) {
		for(int j = 0; j < grid[0].size(); j++) {
			if(grid[i][j] == 1)
				freshOranges++;
			else if(grid[i][j] == 2)
				q.push({i, j});
		}
	}
	```
* *Here we can simply return 0 if fresh oranges count is still 0 after traversing the entire gird as all the oranges given in the grid are already rotten, so 0 time will be taken to rot them.*
3. Now traverse the queue in level order fashion.
	```
	while(!q.empty()) {
		int n = q.size();
        while(n--) {
               //code
		 }
    }
	```

	At every level, take out front of queue and check in its all four directions, whether a fresh orange is present or not, taking care of boundary conditions. If a fresh orange is found, make it rotten, push its index in the queue and decrement fresh oranges count by one.
	```cpp
	int x = q.front().first;
	int y = q.front().second;
	q.pop();
	//top
	if(x - 1 >= 0 && grid[x-1][y] == 1) {
		grid[x-1][y] = 2;
		q.push({x-1, y});
		freshOranges--;
	}
	//left
	if(y - 1 >= 0 && grid[x][y-1] == 1) {
		grid[x][y-1] = 2;
		q.push({x, y-1});
		freshOranges--;
	}
	//down
	if(x + 1 < grid.size() && grid[x+1][y] == 1) {
		grid[x+1][y] = 2;
		q.push({x+1, y});
		freshOranges--;
	}
	//right
	if(y + 1 < grid[0].size() && grid[x][[y+1] == 1) {
		grid[x][y+1] = 2;
		q.push({x, y+1});
		freshOranges--;
	}
	```
	* *Here we can make our code more readable by changing the instructions, like make an array of dx and dy for the adjacent indices i.e.,*
		```
		int dx[] = {0, 0, 1, -1};
		int dy[] = {1, -1, 0, 0};
		```
		*and check for adjacent oranges as*
		```
		for(int i = 0; i < 4; ++i) {
			int nx = x + dx[i], ny = y + dy[i];
            if(nx >= 0 && nx < grid.size() && ny >= 0 && ny < grid[0].size() && grid[nx][ny] == 1) {
				grid[nx][ny] = 2;
                q.push({nx, ny});
                freshOranges--;
			}
		 }
		```
	After traversal of one complete level, we will increment time by one if the queue is not empty. We are incrementing time by checking this conditions as in the last level all oranges will be already rotten. So we don't want to increment our time in that situation.


	So, we ended with:
	```cpp
	while(!q.empty()) {
		int n = q.size();
		while(n--) {
			int x = q.front().first, y = q.front().second;
			q.pop();
			for(int i = 0; i < 4; ++i) {
				int nx = x + dx[i], ny = y + dy[i];
				if(nx >= 0 && nx < grid.size() && ny >= 0 && ny < grid[0].size() && grid[nx][ny] == 1) {
					grid[nx][ny] = 2;
					q.push({nx, ny});
					freshOranges--;
				}
			}
		}
		if(!q.empty())
			time++;
	}
	```
4.	At last, If the number of fresh oranges after the entire process is zero, then return the time elapsed till now. Else return -1 indicating that it’s impossible to rot all the oranges.
	```
	if(freshOranges == 0)
		return time;
	else
		return -1;
	```

**Dry Run:**
Lets' take an example, grid = [[2,1,1],[1,1,0],[0,1,1]]
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/65b22705-0cc9-4afb-93d1-3b6d0ce91b85_1646064148.1020083.jpeg)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/7454109f-fa58-409f-8a4a-618f6ea605c1_1646064162.615776.jpeg)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8ae4ec0f-f5eb-4505-8932-a0f00ead3f77_1646064173.1493309.jpeg)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f0122139-e1cf-49fe-8125-cfc8848cf244_1646064181.6202948.jpeg)


**Complete Code:**
```
int orangesRotting(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {        
	int freshOranges = 0, time = 0;
    queue<pair<int, int>> q;

    for(int i = 0; i < grid.size(); i++) {
		for(int j = 0; j < grid[0].size(); j++) {
			if(grid[i][j] == 1)
				freshOranges++;
            else if(grid[i][j] == 2)
				q.push({i, j});
        }
    }

	int dx[] = {0, 0, 1, -1};
    int dy[] = {1, -1, 0, 0};

    while(!q.empty()) {
		int n = q.size();
        while(n--) {
			int x = q.front().first, y = q.front().second;
            q.pop();
            for(int i = 0; i < 4; ++i) {
				int nx = x + dx[i], ny = y + dy[i];
                if(nx >= 0 && nx < grid.size() && ny >= 0 && ny < grid[0].size() && grid[nx][ny] == 1) {
					grid[nx][ny] = 2;
                    q.push({nx, ny});
                    freshOranges--;
                }
            }
        }
        if(!q.empty())
            time++;
    }

    if(freshOranges == 0)
        return time;
    else
        return -1;
}
```






**Complexity Analysis:**
* *Time Complexity -* `O(n x m) + O(n x m)`  =>  `O(n x m)`
	* `O(n x m)` for first traversal 
	* `O(n x m)` for queue traversal (*Worst Case when there is only one fresh orange and that too in last*)
* *Space Complexity -* `O(n x m)`
	Extra space for queue (*Worst Case: when all given oranges are rotten*)

