solutions.content:
# Intuition
The approach used is a Breadth-First Search (BFS) algorithm, implemented with a Queue data structure, to traverse the grid of oranges, track rotten oranges and count fresh oranges.

# Approach
The algorithm starts by initializing a queue to store the coordinates of rotten oranges found in the grid. Then, the grid is traversed to count the number of fresh oranges and add the rotten oranges' coordinates to the queue. If there are no fresh oranges, the function returns 0 because there is no need for any minute to elapse.

The while loop iterates until the queue is empty. In each iteration, the size of the queue is obtained to process all the elements currently in the queue, which are the rotten oranges found in the previous minute.

For each rotten orange, its adjacent cells are checked, and if they are fresh oranges, they are marked as rotten, added to the queue, and the counter of fresh oranges is decremented. The BFS algorithm continues to the next level by processing all the fresh oranges found in the previous level.

At each iteration of the while loop, the time variable is incremented to keep track of the minutes that have elapsed since the first rotten orange was found.

Finally, if there are no fresh oranges left, the function returns the elapsed time. Otherwise, it returns -1 to indicate that there are still fresh oranges left that cannot be rotten.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n * m), where n and m are the dimensions of the grid because the BFS algorithm must visit every cell in the grid

- Space complexity:
O(n * m), the queue can store up to all the fresh oranges in the worst-case scenario.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    // initialize time variable to 0
    private int time = 0;

    public int orangesRotting(int[][] grid) {
        // get dimensions of grid
        int y = grid.length;
        int x = grid[0].length;

        // create queue to store rotten oranges
        Queue<int[]> rotten = new LinkedList<>();

        // count number of fresh oranges
        int freshOranges = 0;

        // traverse grid to find rotten and fresh oranges
        for (int i = 0; i < y; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < x; j++) {
                if (grid[i][j] == 2) { // if cell contains a rotten orange
                    rotten.offer(new int[]{i, j}); // add its coordinates to the queue
                } else if (grid[i][j] == 1) { // if cell contains a fresh orange
                    freshOranges++; // increment counter of fresh oranges
                }
            }
        }

        // if there are no fresh oranges, return 0
        if (freshOranges == 0) {
            return 0;
        }

        // use BFS algorithm to find minimum time to rot all fresh oranges
        while (!rotten.isEmpty()) { // while there are still rotten oranges to process
            int size = rotten.size(); // get size of current level of BFS tree

            // process all rotten oranges in current level of BFS tree
            for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                int[] temp = rotten.poll(); // get coordinates of next rotten orange
                assert temp != null; // make sure coordinates are not null
                int row = temp[0]; // get row coordinate
                int col = temp[1]; // get column coordinate

                // check adjacent cells to see if they are fresh oranges
                // if so, mark them as rotten, add to queue, and decrement counter of fresh oranges
                if (row > 0 && grid[row - 1][col] == 1) {
                    rotten.offer(new int[]{row - 1, col});
                    grid[row - 1][col] = 2;
                    freshOranges--;
                }
                if (row < y - 1 && grid[row + 1][col] == 1) {
                    rotten.offer(new int[]{row + 1, col});
                    grid[row + 1][col] = 2;
                    freshOranges--;
                }
                if (col > 0 && grid[row][col - 1] == 1) {
                    rotten.offer(new int[]{row, col - 1});
                    grid[row][col - 1] = 2;
                    freshOranges--;
                }
                if (col < x - 1 && grid[row][col + 1] == 1) {
                    rotten.offer(new int[]{row, col + 1});
                    grid[row][col + 1] = 2;
                    freshOranges--;
                }
            }

            time++; // increment time counter for each level of BFS tree
        }

        // if there are still fresh oranges, return -1 to indicate it is impossible to rot all of them
        // otherwise, return elapsed time
        return freshOranges == 0 ? time - 1 : -1;
    }
}
```

